      <intermediateExchange id="4df15dc0-94d4-5140-a777-3b7682ac9aa2" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="000074-87-3" amount="0.12022553132996208" intermediateExchangeId="07a9af51-381d-46b0-8ee1-1a494950a39a" activityLinkId="53d357bc-4568-504c-89cd-414658769310">
        <name xml:lang="en">methylchloride</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Calculated value based on stoichiometric calculations and literature data. 
50.48752g/mol is the molar mass of methylchloride (CH3Cl). 
129.06054g/mol is the molar mass of dimethyldichlorosilane (C2H6Cl2Si). 

Dimethyldichlorosilane  is commercially produced from silicon as intermediate to the chemical industry (European Commission, 2007). The respective production processes is called Müller-Rochow process, in which finely ground silicon reacts with methyl chloride in a fluidized bed reactor at 280-330 °C , using copper as a catalyst (European Commission, 2007). Byproducts of this process are methyltrichlorosilane (5 – 12 %) and trimethylchlorosilane (2 – 4 %), the yield of dimethyldichlorosilane is reported to be &gt;78% (European Commission, 2007). Here, an efficiency of 95% is assumed.
Chemical Reaction:
2 CH3Cl + Si → (CH3)2SiCl2</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="0.12022553132996208" mu="-2.118385872364986" variance="0.0006" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.010025"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="2" completeness="3" temporalCorrelation="2" geographicalCorrelation="2" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="3"/>
        </uncertainty>
